President Jacob Zuma yesterday signed seven new finance bills into law, his office said. The bills were passed by the National Assembly and the National Council of Provinces in the past year and were with the President for ratification.Among the new laws are: The Taxation Laws Amendment Act The purpose of the act is to amend certain provisions of various acts related to the Transfer Duty Act, the Estate Duty Act, the Customs and Excise Act and the Value-Added Tax Act. This is to bring them in line with the new Taxation Laws Amendment Act. The Finance Act This act seeks to provide provisions for the approval of unauthorised expenditure and recovery of unauthorised expenditure.The Unemployment Insurance Amendment Act The purpose of the act is to amend the Unemployment Insurance Act to provide for the extension of unemployment insurance benefits to pupils who are undergoing learnership training as well as to civil servants. It also adjusts the accrual rate of contributors entitlement to unemployment insurance benefits and provides for the process of application for maternity benefits.The legislation further seeks to empower the Unemployment Insurance Board to provide its constitution for the functions of regional appeals committees and to amend a part of the Unemployment Insurance Act to provide for the adjustment of the income replacement rate. The Rates and Monetary Amounts and Amendment of Revenue Laws (Administration) Act The act aims to provide for administrative matters in respect of additional relief under the voluntary disclosure programme.The Rates and Monetary Amounts and Amendment of Revenue Laws Act The act aims to fix the rates of normal tax, amend the Transfer Duty Act, so as to amend the rates of transfer duty and monetary threshold; to amend the Income Tax Act to amend rates of tax and monetary amounts and to amend the Customs and Excise Act. The act further seeks to provide for additional relief under the voluntary disclosure programme and to provide for matters connected therewith.The Tax Administration Laws Amendment Act The main purpose of this legislation is to amend the Income Tax Act to provide for delegation of power to disclose certain information and to remove an obligation to submit a return for a dividend derived from a tax-free investment. The legislation further seeks to amend the Customs and Excise Act to narrow the scope of provisions relating to special economic zones and to align terminology with terminology used in the Special Economic Zones Act, 2014.In addition, the legislation also seeks to amend certain provisions of the Value-Added Tax Act, the Mineral and Petroleum Resources Royalty (Administration) Act as well as the Tax Administration Act. The Adjustments Appropriation Act The law seeks to affect adjustments to the appropriation of money from the National Revenue Fund for the requirements of government in respect of the 2016-17 financial year and to provide for matters incidental thereto.-Samuel Mungadze|samuelm@thenewage.co.za 